n\n<p>How the cell senses its size, however, is not understood. In 2009, two reports suggested that protein gradients could be responsible for the sensing of cell size. You can read a commentary about those articles in <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19619485\">Cell size control: governed by a spatial gradient. - Almeyda and Tyers, Dev. Cell. (2009) 17(1), 3-4<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The phenomenon of cell size homeostasis, whereby cells coordinate\n  growth and division to maintain a uniform cell size, has been an\n  outstanding issue in cell biology for many decades. Two recent studies\n  in Nature in fission yeast demonstrate that a gradient of the polarity\n  factor Pom1 is a sensor of cell length that determines the onset of\n  Cdc2 activation and mitosis.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>These articles demonstrate one way in which cells may sense their size, but most probably several other mechanisms are also in place.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1524,"question_id":1509,"up_vote_count":26,"last_edit_date":1332364472}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1509/how-does-a-cell-know-its-size","last_activity_date":1336624586,"creation_date":1332311826,"answer_count":1,"title":"How does a cell know its size?","body":"<p>Cells come in all sorts of sizes. How do they regulate their cell size to the point where similar cell types have a fairly mono-disperse size distribution?<\/p>\n\n<p>Reasked from <a href=\"http://www.quora.com/How-Does-a-Cell-Know-Its-Size\">http://www.quora.com/How-Does-a-Cell-Know-Its-Size<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":1509,"tags":["cell-biology"],"score":33,"accepted_answer_id":1524,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":620,"up_vote_count":33},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7974275b33c1c13d775152e812b35776?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":558,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/558/kirby","reputation":619,"display_name":"Kirby","accept_rate":52},"an