et better answers if you make it clear what you&#39;re asking. I assume it&#39;s not <i>whether<\/i> cancer is easier to treat if it&#39;s caught early, or <i>if<\/i> lung cancer is hard to treat anyway, I think we both know those things are true. Do you want to know why we don&#39;t screen more? Why lung cancer is hard to treat even when we&#39;ve found it? Why we typically don&#39;t catch lung cancer earlier? These are all questions that can be answered. Overall it&#39;s a good question, though."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/15f9d8beda0341f0a97ab2f4e63d094e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":67,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/67/fomite","reputation":2369,"display_name":"Fomite"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1336554642,"creation_date":1336554642,"body":"<p>There are a number of reasons, generally, why a screening test may fail to decrease cancer mortality rates:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>The screening test may not be very good. I know this seems like an obvious one, but its something of a problem - a screening test will only reduce mortality if it catches cases that are both <em>treatable<\/em> and wouldn't be detected in time to treat using other methods. For example, it may be that even if caught slightly later by other methods, lung cancer is equally treatable (or equally difficult to treat).<\/li>\n<li>Mortality from false positive tests and subsequent procedures in non-cases offsets any gain in survival among cases.<\/li>\n<li>Diagnosis is only one step toward treating a disease. Even if detected, if a disease is not treatable or isn't treated, knowing you have the disease doesn't change your mortality risk.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>In this case it appears that a chest radiograph isn't good enough at detecting lung cancer to manifestly improve mortality outcomes. The author's of the paper don't really specify <em>why<\/em> this is - though since they're just looking at lung cancer mortality, it's likely not #2.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2209,"question_id":2171,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2171/why-doesnt-yearly-screening-for-lung-cancer-decrease-mortality-rates","last_activity_date":1336554642,"creation_date":1336449495,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why doesn't yearly screening for lung cancer decrease mortality rates?","body":"<p>In a <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22031728\">large trial<\/a>, screening yearly for lung cancer hasn't reduced mortality rates. Why is this? Isn't cancer best treatable when caught early? Is this because lung cancer is hard to treat anyway, because yearly is not frequent enough, or why?<\/p>\n","question_id":2171,"tags":["epidemiology","cancer"],"score":8,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":104,"up_vote_count":9,"last_edit_date":1336482346},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d117d782e1f2d2706ddabe1febee315c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":835,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/835/robert-long","reputation":251,"display_name":"Robert Long"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3bb465ba7c2338b41ef15a2a05306a7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":444,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/444/gianpaolo-r","reputation":3120,"display_name":"Gianpaolo R","accept_rate":40},"score":10,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d117d782e1f2d2706ddabe1febee315c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":835,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/835/robert-long","reputation":251,"display_name":"Robert Long"},"score":0,"post_id":2173,"edited":false,"creation_date":1336475110,"comment_id":2895,"body":"Great answer. Thank you ! I would upvote, but I don&#39;t have sufficient rep myself (yet). Just a further query: when I read: &quot;facilitate fat uptake and storage&quot; would I be right in saying the /primary/ function is fat uptake, which then results in fat storage (in adipocytes)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/35114dfb827dc71cb3a8ff281617c5b8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":535,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/535/larry-parnell","reputation":3430,"display_name":"Larry_Parnell"},"score":0,"post_id":2173,"edited":false,"creation_date":1336488131,"comment_id":2898,"body":"No. All cells need fats, primarily to build membranes and to store in vesicles for later conversion to energy. Storage is not restricted to adipocytes."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d117d782e1f2d2706ddabe1febee315c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":835,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/835/robert-long","reputation":251,"display_name":"Robert Long"},"score":0,"post_id":2173,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/35114dfb827dc71cb3a8ff281617c5b8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":535,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/535/larry-parnell","reputation":3430,"display_name":"Larry_Parnell"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1336493360,"comment_id":2900,"body":"@Larry_Parnell Sorry, by writing &quot;(adipocytes)&quot; I meant to query whether the /primary/ function of LPL in adipose tissue is fat storage ? I took home from the answer is that LPL <b>performs<\/b> fat uptake and thereby <b>facilitates<\/b> fat storage."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d117d782e1f2d2706ddabe1febee315c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":835,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/835/robert-long","reputation":251,"display_name":"Robert Long"},"score":0,"post_id":2173,"edited":false,"creation_date":1336493493,"comment_id":2901,"body":"+1 by the way :)"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1336503325,"creation_date":1336472303,"body":"<p>Fat uptake means cells eating fat.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'll try to keep it simple, so forget the many approximations. You need first to consider that most fat circulates in the blood under the form of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triglyceride\" rel=\"nofollow\">triglycerides (TG)<\/a>. TG are not soluble in water, so how do they circulate? They are hidden inside cargo vehicles called <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lipoprotein\" rel=\"nofollow\">lipoproteins<\/a>. When a circulating lipoprotein touches a cell, if the cell expresses lipoprotein lipase (LPL), first LPL would trap the lipoprotein cargo, and then will start to catabolize the TG.<\/p>\n\n<p>Importantly, there are no efficient TG cargoes inside the cell, so <strong>the function of lipoprotein lipase<\/strong> is to make fat easy to move inside the cell. TG are a chemical assembly of one glycerol and three fatty acids. Of note, there are good fatty acid cargoes inside the cell, so LPL will break TG into glycerol and fatty acids so that <a href=\"http://www.wiley.com/legacy/college/boyer/0470003790/animations/fatty_acid_metabolism/fatty_acid_metabolism.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">they can be further metabolized<\/a> depending on the cell type.<\/p>\n\n<p>Heart and muscle cells will bring fatty acids to mitochondria where they will be oxidized to produce energy. With reference to your question, adipocyte cells will bring fatty acids to other cellular compartments where they will be converted back to triglycerides and stored as fat. That's why you read that LPL facilitates fat uptake and storage in adipose tissue.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2173,"question_id":2172,"up_vote_count":10,"last_edit_date":1336503325}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2172/primary-function-of-the-enzyme-lipoprotein-lipase","last_activity_date":1336503325,"creation_date":1336466694,"answer_count":1,"title":"Primary function of the enzyme lipoprotein lipase","body":"<p>I read <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/?file=/ijo/journal/v21/n9/abs/0800473a.html\">here<\/a> and <a href=\"http://jas.fass.org/content/48/6/1530.full.pdf\">here<\/a> that the function of lipoprotein lipase is to facilitate fat uptake and storage in adipose tissue. Could anyone provide a slightly more expanded explanation, without going into too much detail, and without the use of too much jargon (I am not a biologist). I have read the wikipedia page, but sadly I didn't understand it....Thanks !<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit: One of the things that is confusing me is what \"fat uptake\" means in this context.<\/p>\n","question_id":2172,"tags":["human-biology","metabolism"],"score":8,"accepted_answer_id":2173,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":7201,"up_vote_count":9,"last_edit_date":1336469083},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/81e60a23afa4ef8c392a56e27731c2db?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":846,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/846/user1030497","reputation":23,"display_name":"user1030497"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/55b2cca3b7a11df3a961d57a68705503?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":43,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/43/daniel-standage","reputation":3502,"display_name":"Daniel Standage","accept_rate":76},"score":7,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1336499135,"creation_date":1336499135,"body":"<p>Although each cell of your body essentially contains the same DNA and the same genes, cells in different tissues express (turn on) different genes under different conditions. Measuring differential gene expression involves looking at the amount of expression for a gene (or set of genes) in two contrasting scenarios. The contrast could be across different times, different tissues, different conditions, different related species, etc.<\/p>\n\n<p>When, you say a gene is \"differentially expressed\", this is very context-specific. The phrase means nothing by itself, and it is only useful in terms of the applicable contrast. For example, the statement \"gene A is differentially expressed\" is uninformative, while the statement \"gene A is differentially expressed in liver and muscle tissue\" is descriptive--it tells you that liver tissues and muscle tissues have a significantly different level of gene A products. Often the terms \"up-regulated\" and \"down-regulated\" are also used to provide additional detail. In the context of the previous example, the statement \"gene A is up-regulated in muscle tissues\" tells you that the level of gene A products is higher in muscle tissues than in liver tissues.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2178,"question_id":2176,"up_vote_count":7}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2176/what-exactly-is-meant-by-the-expression-differentially-expressed","last_activity_date":1336499135,"creation_date":1336496143,"answer_count":1,"title":"What exactly is meant by the expression \"differentially expressed\"?","body":"<p>As far as I've seen, this expression is almost always used in relation to gene expression profiling. Unfortunately, I have no background in this area. Can someone please explain this in layman terms?<\/p>\n","question_id":2176,"tags":["genetics","gene-expression"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":2178,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":203,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1336498478},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/75a35d91ad143e63c8ad907c611ee673?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":135,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/135/johnny1bucket","reputation":159,"display_name":"johnny1bucket"},"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user24"},"score":5,"post_id":91,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323967721,"comment_id":92,"body":"In order to attract the experts, we should probably avoid wide and basic questions this early in the beta."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":91,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323994905,"comment_id":140,"body":"This question has brought up <a href=\"http://meta.biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17/should-we-encourange-the-relevant-questions-from-non-professionals\">a discussion on meta<\/a>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3eeb23bd64f5e7f488a15ef25261e4df?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":148,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/148/dr-dredel","reputation":280,"display_name":"Dr.Dredel"},"score":6,"post_id":91,"edited":false,"creation_date":1324023698,"comment_id":162,"body":"I would argue that if someone is so &quot;expert&quot; as to be driven away by a question like this, then good-riddance. Sure, you want to stay on topic, but come-on! This was a terrific question, and a REALLY informative and well thought out answer. A little less technical than the ideal? possibly, but closing it is an overreaction."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"score":1,"post_id":91,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3eeb23bd64f5e7f488a15ef25261e4df?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":148,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/148/dr-dredel","reputation":280,"display_name":"Dr.Dredel"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1324096860,"comment_id":183,"body":"@Dr.Dredel please see the discussion on meta and comment there"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avat