pe":"registered","user_id":444,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/444/gianpaolo-r","reputation":3120,"display_name":"Gianpaolo R","accept_rate":40},"score":10,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e1d3326342ee9de40822577d766465e8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":72,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/72/yamad","reputation":2340,"display_name":"yamad"},"score":0,"post_id":2175,"edited":false,"creation_date":1336534189,"comment_id":2908,"body":"+1. Neurons use a lot of active transport pumps that consume ATP to maintain ion gradients and to shuttle neurotransmitters."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1336491003,"creation_date":1336491003,"body":"<p>There is a good review in the Journal of Experimental Biology (Bickler and Donohoe 2002, <a href=\"http://jeb.biologists.org/content/205/23/3579.full.pdf\">JEB 205, 3579\u20133585<\/a>) I will just summarize for those that do not have access to the review.<\/p>\n\n<p>Neurons use lot of energy to maintain their polarized state, this is not required to other cells. When O2 or blood flow is reduced, the neuronal ATP levels breaks down very fast, with 90% ATP depleted in less than 5 minutes. Without ATP, the neuron can not maintain the correct ion flux, so depolarization occurs causing <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Excitotoxicity\">glutamate excitotoxicity<\/a>, cell swelling and finally cell death.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2175,"question_id":2133,"up_vote_count":10}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2133/why-do-neurons-die-so-quickly-relative-to-other-cells-when-deprived-of-oxygen","last_activity_date":1336491109,"creation_date":1336316491,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do neurons die so quickly (relative to other cells) when deprived of oxygen?","body":"<p>This question could be considered a follow-up question to <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/755/why-is-a-lack-of-oxygen-fatal-to-cells\">Why is a lack of oxygen fatal to cells?<\/a>, although the top answer there does not address why damage starts to pop in.<\/p>\n\n<p>The answer says this:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Neurons are also highly metabolically active, which means they\n  generate more waste products. A buildup of nitrogenous waste products\n  in the cell (and bloodstream) can be potentially fatal due to it's\n  effects on pH (screws up enzymes and a whole slew of biochemical\n  reactions)<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>But when the brain is deprived of oxygen, metabolism shuts down. So waste products aren't being generated anymore.<\/p>\n\n<p>====<\/p>\n\n<p>Basically I'm wondering - what causes neurons, in particular, to die so quickly (relative to other cells, like kidney cells) after they're depleted of energy?<\/p>\n","question_id":2133,"tags":["neuroscience","cellular-respiration"],"score":12,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1402,"up_vote_count":12,"last_edit_date":1336491109},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4da5942f8b5d2c1fda861e780187b113?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":333,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/333/ebvirus","reputation":59,"display_name":"Ebvirus"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b219b646efa3c74061977c39306c1841?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":810,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/810/shep","reputation":1198,"display_name":"Shep","accept_rate":67},"score":0,"post_id":624,"edited":false,"creation_date":1336466628,"comment_id":2891,"body":"I assume blackbody radiation doesn&#39;t count?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9f137c8bccd23ae845550c5e95c1e31b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4821,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4821/rodrigo","reputation":478,"display_name":"Rodrigo"},"score":0,"post_id":624,"edited":false,"creation_date":1