ther more serious abnormalities can cause this problem.  Duct cysts or hemangiomas can also cause tear duct blockages in more severe cases.  Various factors, such as anatomical abnormalities and problems with pumping tears increase the propensity for the disorder in children with Trisomy-21 [2].  As nico has alluded to in the comments, there may be a lag in the development of the physiology of tear production even in non-Trisomy-21 children.  <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>[1] Thomas K. McInerny, MD, FAAP, ed. 2009. American Academy of Pediatrics Textbook of Pediatric Care. Elk Grove Village, IL. American Academy of Pediatrics, p1706.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>[2]M. E. Wilson et al. (eds.), Pediatric Ophthalmology, 2009, pp. 276-284.  DOI 10.1007/978-3-540-68632-3_1.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":2117,"question_id":2116,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1336308814}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2116/is-it-true-that-newborn-babies-dont-produce-tears-while-crying-why","last_activity_date":1336308814,"creation_date":1336215355,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is it true that newborn babies don't produce tears while crying? Why?","body":"<p>Well, I was just going through an article on eye, where in fun facts it was mentioned that newly born (for initial 1 to 3 months) babies do not produce tear while crying. Actually, I have found this true. <\/p>\n\n<p>Now, I am wondering why is it so? Does any one know the reason behind this?<\/p>\n","question_id":2116,"tags":["human-biology","eyes"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":2117,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1262,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1336218548},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24c0e23c30888c23e2d4fe9991cf2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":57,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/57/jonsca","reputation":3367,"display_name":"jonsca","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user56