with the nature of the afferent neurons (Ia fibers), which carry a signal into the spinal cord and synapse onto motor neurons directly.  See <a href=\"http://neuroscience.uth.tmc.edu/s3/chapter01.html\">this text<\/a> (scroll down to section 1.10) for a diagram.  At their other end, these Ia fibers penetrate into the muscle and wrap themselves around the body of the muscle spindles, <code>\"[which] are specialized receptors that signal (a) the length and (b) the rate of change of length (velocity) of the muscle.\"<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>Because the main role of these spindles is to monitor the muscles for very rapid changes in length, the neurons have a static range which is optimized for these quick jerks (rather than firing over a wide range of velocities).  When you are stretching the muscle slowly, the Ia fiber is not building up a sufficient depolarization to fire off an action potential.    <\/p>\n","answer_id":2095,"question_id":2089,"up_vote_count":6}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2089/why-is-the-patellar-reflex-not-triggered-when-the-tendon-is-extended-slowly","last_activity_date":1336088546,"creation_date":1336069278,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why is the Patellar reflex not triggered when the tendon is extended slowly?","body":"<p>I have been previously told that the Patellar reflex (knee-jerk-reaction) exists to prevent the hyper-extension of the patellar tendon.  Yet if the impact to the tendon is delivered slowly - i.e. by pressing down on it rather than striking it - there is no reflex response.  Why is this, as surely the tendon is being extended by the same amount? <\/p>\n","question_id":2089,"tags":["human-biology","neuroscience","reflexes"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":2095,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":271,"up_vote_count":7},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d8ead42ce4d3f10483cf843ba28ae86a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":695,"link":"http://biology.stackex