n an accessible format with several examples and extensive illustrations. <\/p>\n","answer_id":1947,"question_id":1917,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/15f9d8beda0341f0a97ab2f4e63d094e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":67,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/67/fomite","reputation":2369,"display_name":"Fomite"},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5aab27ac128d8b89b554faa71f4b114d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":777,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/777/ricardo-altamirano","reputation":140,"display_name":"Ricardo Altamirano"},"score":0,"post_id":1996,"edited":false,"creation_date":1335561586,"comment_id":2596,"body":"Excellent answer. The other post you linked is also extremely helpful. I actually had Rothman&#39;s beginner introduction in the stack of books I borrowed from my uni&#39;s library already, and upon first read I quite like it. Thank you!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1335506220,"creation_date":1335506220,"body":"<p>There are two books I'd highly recommend for someone starting to dabble in Epidemiology. The first is Kenneth Rothman's <em>Epidemiology: An Introduction<\/em>, which I'm affectionately going to refer to as \"Baby Rothman\" from hereon out for reasons that will become obvious.<\/p>\n\n<p>Baby Rothman is an excellent \"getting your feet wet\" book. It's simplistic, and clearly designed for someone with no background in Epidemiology, so it starts from things that, if you have a statistical background, you might find a bit dull. But it accomplishes two key tasks:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>A basic treatment of the subject from a pre-eminent methodologist and advocate for the field that doesn't make some of the sloppy slight-of-hand mistakes many introductory books do.<\/li>\n<li>An introduction to the \"vocabulary\" of Epidemiology as a field - what we call things, how we thing about effect estimates, etc.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>The second book I would buy would be <em>Modern Epidemiology: 3rd Edition<\/em> by Rothman, Greenland and Lash. This is <em>the<\/em> definitive reference book for most epidemiological methods  currently used in the field. As I said on a related <a href=\"http://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/21405/good-reference-book-for-epidemiology\">CrossValidated<\/a> question, ME3 is the only epidemiology book that has always come with me, regardless of what project I'm doing, and which I have routinely found invaluable.<\/p>\n\n<p>The other benefit of the book is that it's \"platform agnostic\". It's not going to try to teach you a statistics package - its going to teach you the science and philosophy of Epidemiology, the actual doing of the science, rather than the toolkit. Without that kind of methodological rigor, you can be a wizard at your language of choice and still do bad science.<\/p>\n\n<p>If I were only going to buy one book, it would be ME3.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1996,"question_id":1917,"up_vote_count":6}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1917/could-someone-recommend-an-introductory-book-on-epidemiology","last_activity_date":1335506220,"creation_date":1335053995,"answer_count":4,"title":"Could someone recommend an introductory book on epidemiology?","body":"<p>I'm hoping to learn the basics of epidemiological methods, terminology, etc. I come from a background in statistical economics, and I'm moving into the economics of public health. I don't know if epidemiology uses separate statistical methods, but I presume it does. I know discussion questions aren't recommended, but please list any reasons you have (personal experience, ease of introduction, etc.) for texts you would recommend. <\/p>\n","question_id":1917,"tags":["epidemiology"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":1996,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"not constructive","is_answered":true,"view_count":1181,"up_vote_count":5}]